-- TABLE-Qatar June M2 growth lowest since April 2012, lending up
-- By Martin Dokoupil
-- Sun Jul 27, 2014 07:31AM EDT
-- None



July 27 (Reuters) - Money supply (M2) growth in Qatar slowed to 4.8 percent year-on-year at the end of June, the slowest rate since April 2012, from 9.6 percent in the previous month, central bank data showed on Sunday.

Total bank credit grew 11.3 percent on an annual basis in June, up from 9.8 percent in May. Non-resident deposits fell 17.9 percent on an annual basis and 3.6 percent month-on-month to 33.2 billion riyals ($9.1 billion).